com.gwtplatform.mvp.client.proxy

Class NotifyingAsyncCallback<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.gwtplatform.mvp.client.proxy.NotifyingAsyncCallback<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of the return value. See AsyncCallback.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    AsyncCallback<T>

    public abstract class NotifyingAsyncCallback<T>
extends Object
implements AsyncCallback<T>
    An implementation of AsyncCallback that sends events on the EventBus whenever an async call starts, succeeds, or fails. The events fired are AsyncCallStartEvent, AsyncCallSucceedEvent, AsyncCallFailEvent.

    So the way to use NotifyingAsyncCallback is the following: 

       NotifyingAsyncCallback callback = new NotifyingAsyncCallback(eventBus) { ... };
   callback.prepare();
   someRpcMethod(callback);
   callback.checkLoading();
    Author:
    Philippe Beaudoin

      • prepare

        public void prepare()
        This method is used to place that the async callback in its INITIALIZED stated. It should be call prior to invoking any RPC that takes this callback as a parameter. See NotifyingAsyncCallback for usage.

      • checkLoading

        public void checkLoading()
        This method is used to indicate that the async callback is currently loading. It will not do anything if the call is already finished (i.e. in the case of an immediate failure or success). See NotifyingAsyncCallback for usage.

      • success

        protected abstract void success(T result)
        This method is called whenever the asynchronous call returns successfully.
        Parameters:
        result - the return value of the remote produced call.

      • failure

        protected void failure(Throwable caught)
        This method is called whenever the asynchronous call returns with a failure. Override this method if you want to perform clean-up operation when an async call fails. The default implementation is empty.
        Parameters:
        caught - failure encountered while executing a remote procedure call.
